#### Green belt

*Further information: [West Midlands Green Belt](/West_Midlands_Green_Belt)*

Worcester sits within a regional [green belt](/Green_belt_(United_Kingdom)) that extends into the surrounding counties. This policy is designed to curb [urban sprawl](/Urban_sprawl) between the towns and cities of the nearby [West Midlands conurbation](/West_Midlands_conurbation), which is centered around [Birmingham](/Birmingham) and [Coventry](/Coventry_and_Bedworth_Urban_Area). The goals are to prevent these urban areas from merging, protect the distinct identities of outlying communities, encourage the redevelopment of [brownfield](/Brownfield) sites, and preserve the surrounding [countryside](/Countryside). This is achieved by restricting inappropriate development within designated areas and imposing stringent conditions on any building that is permitted. [58]

Within the city's boundary, there is a small pocket of green belt located north of the Worcester and Birmingham canal and the suburbs of Perdiswell and Northwick. This is part of a larger, isolated tract of green belt south of the main zone, which extends into the neighboring Wychavon district. This helps to minimize urban sprawl between Fernhill Heath and Droitwich Spa, maintaining their separation. The green belt was first established under [Worcestershire County Council](/Worcestershire_County_Council) in 1975; as of 2017, the area within the borough amounted to some 240 hectares (2.4 km²; 0.93 sq mi). [59]

### Demography and religion

The 2011 census placed Worcester's population at 98,768. Approximately 93.4 percent of residents were classified as white, with 89.1 percentage points of that group identifying as [White British](/White_British)—a figure higher than the national average. [60] The largest religious group is [Christians](/Christianity), accounting for 63.7 percent of the city's population. [60] Those who reported having [no religion](/Irreligion) or declined to state their beliefs made up 32.3 percent. The next largest religious group, [Muslims](/Muslims), comprised 2.9 percent. The city's ethnic minorities include people of [Pakistani](/British_Pakistani), [Bangladeshi](/Bangladeshis), [Chinese](/British_Chinese), [Indian](/British_Indian), [Italian](/Italian_British), and [Polish](/Polish_British) origin. The largest single minority group is [British Pakistanis](/British_Pakistanis), numbering around 1,900, or 1.95 percent of the population. This has resulted in Worcester having a small but diverse array of religious groups. Alongside the dominant Anglican [Worcester Cathedral](/Worcester_Cathedral), there are also [Catholic](/Catholicism), [United Reformed](/United_Reformed_Church), [61] and [Baptist](/Baptist) churches, a substantial center for [the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints](/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints), a few [Islamic](/Islamic) mosques, and several smaller groups for oriental religions such as [Buddhism](/Buddhism) and the [International Society for Krishna Consciousness](/International_Society_for_Krishna_Consciousness).

Worcester is the seat of a [Church of England](/Church_of_England) bishop, whose official signature is their personal Christian name followed by *Wigorn*., an abbreviation of the Latin *Wigorniensis*, meaning "of Worcester". [62] This is also occasionally used to abbreviate the county's name. The previous [Archdeacon of Worcester](/List_of_Archdeacons_of_Worcester), [Robert Jones](/Robert_Jones_(Archdeacon_of_Worcester)), who was inducted in November 2014, had previously served as Rector of St Barnabas with Christ Church in Worcester for eight years. [63] He retired on 30 November 2023. [64]

### Economy

#### Manufacturing

One of Worcester's most globally recognized products, [Lea & Perrins](/Lea_%26_Perrins) [Worcestershire sauce](/Worcestershire_sauce), is still manufactured and bottled at its Midland Road factory, its home since 16 October 1897. The original Lea and Perrins partnership began in a chemist's shop that once stood on the site of the Debenhams store in the Crowngate Shopping Centre. Worcester is also home to what is claimed to be the [oldest newspaper in the world](/List_of_the_oldest_newspapers) still in publication: [Berrow's Worcester Journal](/Berrow%27s_Worcester_Journal). Its lineage can be traced back to a news-sheet first published in 1690. [65]

The city's foundry heritage is carried on by Morganite Crucible at Norton, which produces graphitic shaped products and cements for modern industrial applications. [66] The city is also the location of the European manufacturing plant of [Yamazaki Mazak Corporation](/Yamazaki_Mazak_Corporation), a global [Japanese](/Japan) [machine tool builder](/Machine_tool_builder) that established its presence here in 1980. [67] Worcester Heating Systems was founded in the city in 1962 by [Cecil Duckworth](/Cecil_Duckworth). The company was later acquired by Bosch and rebranded as [Worcester Bosch](/Worcester,_Bosch_Group) in 1996. [68] [69]

#### Retail trade

The city serves as a major retail center, featuring several covered shopping centers that house major chain stores, alongside numerous independent shops and restaurants, particularly concentrated in Friar Street and New Street. The main shopping artery is the High Street, which was controversially part-modernised in 2005 and further updated in 2015, with ongoing redevelopment of the Cathedral Plaza and Lychgate Shopping Centre. Much of the public outcry during these works centered on the felling of old trees, the protracted duration of the work (delayed by weather and an archaeological discovery), and the removal of historic flagstones outside the city's 18th-century Guildhall. [70] Other key thoroughfares include the Shambles and Broad Street. The Cross and its immediate vicinity function as the city's financial district, home to the main branches of most major banks.

[CrownGate Shopping Centre](/CrownGate_Shopping_Centre), Cathedral Plaza, and Reindeer Court are the three primary covered shopping centers. Just east of the city center lies the unenclosed shopping area of Shrub Hill Retail Park in the St Martin's Quarter. In the [inner suburbs](/Inner_suburb), the Elgar and Blackpole retail parks in the Blackpole district host a variety of nationwide retail chains.

### Amenities and landmarks

The most inescapable landmark in Worcester is the Anglican [Worcester Cathedral](/Worcester_Cathedral). Officially known as the Cathedral Church of Christ and the Blessed Virgin Mary, it was called Worcester Priory before the [English Reformation](/English_Reformation). Construction on the current structure began in 1084. Its crypt is even older, dating from the 11th century. The cathedral boasts the only circular chapter house in the country and serves as the final resting place for [King John](/John_of_England) and [Prince Arthur](/Arthur,_Prince_of_Wales). Nearby stands the spire of St Andrew's Church, a solitary survivor after the rest of the church was demolished in 1949 due to safety concerns. Known as [Glover's Needle](/Glover%27s_Needle), a nod to the city's historic glove-making industry, it holds the title of the steepest church spire in the UK. [71] [72]

The Parish Church of St Helen, located on the north side of the High Street, is a predominantly medieval building, though its west tower was rebuilt in 1813. The east end, re-fenestration, and porch were completed by [Frederick Preedy](/Frederick_Preedy) between 1857 and 1863. Further restoration work was carried out by [Aston Webb](/Aston_Webb) in 1879–1880. It is a Grade II* [listed building](/Listed_building). [73]

A brass plate on a wall adjacent to the riverside path leading to the cathedral marks the high-water levels from the great flood of 1670 and more recent floods, a stark reminder of the river's power.

The city's museums include the Worcester City Art Gallery and Museum, Greyfriars' House, the Infirmary Museum, Tudor House Museum, George Marshall Medical Museum, RAF Defford Museum, Museum of Royal Worcester, Mercian Regiment Museum, the Commandery, and the Worcestershire Yeomanry Museum. The site of the Battle of Worcester is located just south of the city. Limited sections of Worcester's original [city wall](/Worcester_city_walls) also remain.

[The Hive](/The_Hive,_Worcester), situated on the north bank of the [River Severn](/River_Severn) on the former cattle market site, is Worcester's combined public and university library and archive center. Heralded as "the first of its kind in Europe," its distinctive design, with seven towers and a golden rooftop, has made it a prominent feature on the skyline. It has garnered international recognition, winning two [awards](/Worcester_Hive_Awards) for its building design and sustainability. [74] [75]

Worcester's three main open spaces are [Gheluvelt Park](/Gheluvelt_Park,_Worcester) in the Barbourne suburb; [Fort Royal Park](/Fort_Royal_Hill) in the south-east, a short walk from the Commandery and the site of the final battle of the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War) in 1651; [76] and Cripplegate Park, on the right bank of the river adjacent to the Worcester County Cricket ground, which offers a variety of leisure facilities. [78] The large Gheluvelt Park commemorates the role of the [Worcestershire Regiment](/Worcestershire_Regiment)'s 2nd Battalion in the [Battle of Gheluvelt](/Battle_of_Gheluvelt) during the [First World War](/World_War_I). [77] An additional large open space, known as [Pitchcroft](/Worcester_Racecourse), lies close to the city center on the east bank of the [River Severn](/River_Severn). This 100-acre (40-hectare) area is a public space, except on days when it is used for [horse racing](/Horse_racing).

A statue of the composer [Edward Elgar](/Edward_Elgar), created by Kenneth Potts and unveiled in 1981, stands at the end of Worcester High Street, looking towards the cathedral. It is positioned just a few meters from the original site of his father's music shop, which was demolished in the 1960s. [79] Elgar was born in the nearby village of [Broadheath](/Broadheath,_Worcestershire). Plaques installed around the city include a dedication to the medieval Jewish community on Copenhagen Street. [80]

The city has two large wooded areas: Perry Wood, spanning 12 hectares (30 acres), and Nunnery Wood, covering 21 hectares (52 acres). Local legend often claims Perry Wood as the site where [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell) met and made a pact with the Devil. [81] Nunnery Wood is an integral part of the adjacent [Worcester Woods Country Park](/Worcester_Woods_Country_Park), located next to [County Hall](/County_Hall,_Worcester) on the city's east side.

### Transport

#### Road

The [M5 Motorway](/M5_Motorway) runs north–south just to the east of the city, accessible via junction 6 (Worcester North) and junction 7 (Worcester South). This connects Worcester to most of the country, including London, which is 118 miles (190 km) away via the scenic [A44](/A44_road) through the [Cotswolds](/Cotswolds) and the [M40](/M40_motorway). A faster, though longer, route of 134 miles (216 km) utilizes the [M5](/M5_motorway), [M42](/M42_motorway), and [M40](/M40_motorway) motorways.

Main roads passing through the city include the [A449 road](/A449_road), which heads south-west to [Malvern](/Malvern,_Worcestershire) and north to [Kidderminster](/Kidderminster). The [A44](/A44_road) runs south-east to [Evesham](/Evesham) and west towards [Leominster](/Leominster) and [Aberystwyth](/Aberystwyth), crossing Worcester Bridge. The [A38](/A38_road) trunk road extends south to [Tewkesbury](/Tewkesbury) and [Gloucester](/Gloucester), and north-north-east to [Droitwich](/Droitwich), [Bromsgrove](/Bromsgrove), and [Birmingham](/Birmingham). The [A4103](/A4103_road) travels west-south-west to [Hereford](/Hereford), and the [A422](/A422) heads east to [Alcester](/Alcester), branching from the A44 east of the M5. The city is partially encircled by the A4440 ring road.

Carrington Bridge on the A4440 is the second [road bridge across the Severn](/Crossings_of_the_River_Severn). Opened on 20 April 1985 after decades of calls for a second bridge to alleviate traffic on the narrow city center bridge, it connects the A38 from Gloucester with the A449 to [Malvern](/Malvern,_Worcestershire). It is one of Worcestershire's busiest roads. The original single-carriageway bridge was dualled, with work completed on 5 August 2022, making the Southern Link Road a dual carriageway between M5 junction 7 and the Powick Roundabout. As of 2025, it remains the only river crossing in the 10-mile (16 km) stretch between Worcester and [Upton-upon-Severn](/Upton-upon-Severn). [83] [84]

#### Rail

Worcester is served by three railway stations. [Worcester Foregate Street](/Worcester_Foregate_Street_railway_station) is located centrally, [Worcester Shrub Hill](/Worcester_Shrub_Hill_railway_station) is just over 0.5 miles (0.80 km) to the east, and [Worcestershire Parkway](/Worcestershire_Parkway_railway_station), which opened in 2020, is situated 4.5 miles (7.2 km) south-east of the city center. Collectively, they serve [all stations](/List_of_railway_stations_in_Worcestershire) in the county and provide frequent services to Birmingham and the North, Oxford and London ([Paddington](/Paddington_railway_station)), [Malvern](/Malvern,_Worcestershire) and [Hereford](/Hereford), as well as Cardiff, Bristol, and the [West Country](/West_Country). [85]

#### Buses

*See also: [Worcestershire bus route 144](/Worcestershire_bus_route_144)*

The primary bus operator in and around the city is [First Midland Red](/First_Midland_Red). Several smaller operators, including Astons, DRM, and LMS Travel, also provide services. [Diamond Bus](/Diamond_West_Midlands) runs a service from [Kidderminster](/Kidderminster) to communities along the A449. The main terminus and interchange for most bus services is Crowngate bus station in the city center.

The city previously had two park and ride sites: one off the A38 in Perdiswell and another at [Sixways Stadium](/Sixways_Stadium) near the M5. [Worcestershire County Council](/Worcestershire_County_Council) voted to close both in 2014 as part of budget cuts. [86] The service at Sixways Stadium has since been reinstated, with LMS Travel operating the W3 route to [Worcestershire Royal Hospital](/Worcestershire_Royal_Hospital), though it now bypasses the city center bus station. [87]

#### Air

Worcester's nearest major airport is [Birmingham International](/Birmingham_Airport), 35 miles (56 km) away. It is accessible by motorway in about 40 minutes, or by rail via [Birmingham New Street station](/Birmingham_New_Street_station), from which direct trains to the airport take 10-12 minutes and run frequently. [Gloucestershire Airport](/Gloucestershire_Airport) in [Staverton](/Staverton,_Gloucestershire), about 24 miles (39 km) away, is the UK's busiest general aviation airport for business and private charters, flying clubs, and pilot training. [88]

#### Cycling

Worcester is situated on routes 45 and 46 of the National Cycle Network. [89] Various cycle routes exist around the city. [Diglis](/Diglis) Bridge, a pedestrian and [cycle bridge](/Cycling_infrastructure) across the Severn, opened in 2010, connecting St Peter's with [Lower Wick](/Lower_Wick,_Worcester). [90] In 2024, [Beryl](/Beryl_(company)) bikes were introduced for hire across the city, providing 175 [e-bikes](/Electric_bicycle) and 50 pedal bikes from a network of 53 bays. [91]

#### Waterways

The [River Severn](/River_Severn) is navigable through Worcester and connects to the [Worcester and Birmingham Canal](/Worcester_and_Birmingham_Canal), linking the city with Birmingham and the wider national canal network. Once vital arteries for transporting goods, the canals are now primarily used for leisure boating.

### Education

The secondary schools within the city are [Bishop Perowne CofE College](/Bishop_Perowne_CofE_College), [Blessed Edward Oldcorne Catholic College](/Blessed_Edward_Oldcorne_Catholic_College), [Christopher Whitehead Language College](/Christopher_Whitehead_Language_College), [Tudor Grange Academy](/Tudor_Grange_Academy,_Worcester), [Nunnery Wood High School](/Nunnery_Wood_High_School), and the [New College Worcester](/New_College_Worcester), which caters specifically to blind and partially sighted pupils aged 11–18. The city is also home to some of the country's oldest [independent schools](/Independent_schools). The [Royal Grammar School](/Royal_Grammar_School_Worcester), founded in 1291, merged with the [Alice Ottley School](/Alice_Ottley_School) in 2007. [The King's School](/The_King%27s_School,_Worcester), located within the grounds of [Worcester Cathedral](/Worcester_Cathedral), was re-founded in 1541 under King [Henry VIII](/Henry_VIII_of_England). Other independent schools include the Independent Christian School, the [River School](/River_School) in [Fernhill Heath](/Fernhill_Heath), and [New College Worcester](/New_College_Worcester).

The [University of Worcester](/University_of_Worcester) was granted full university status in 2005 by the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom). It was previously known as University College Worcester (UCW) from 1997, and before that as Worcester College of Higher Education. The city also has two colleges: [Worcester Sixth Form College](/Worcester_Sixth_Form_College) and [Heart of Worcestershire College](/Heart_of_Worcestershire_College).

### Hospitals

The [Worcestershire Royal Hospital](/Worcestershire_Royal_Hospital) is the main [NHS](/NHS) hospital serving the city and county, having opened in 2002 to replace the Worcester Royal Infirmary. The former Worcester Eye Hospital was based in the Grade II listed Thornloe House on Barbourne Road from 1940 to 1995. [92] St Oswald's Hospital on the Tything, originally founded as almshouses, is now a care home. [93]

### Sport

*   [Worcestershire County Cricket Club](/Worcestershire_County_Cricket_Club) is one of the 18 [first-class cricket](/First-class_cricket) clubs competing in the [County Championship](/County_Championship). [94] The club's home ground is [New Road](/New_Road,_Worcester).
*   [Worcester City Football Club](/Worcester_City_F.C.), established in 1902, plays in the [Southern Football League](/Southern_Football_League) Premier Division Central, the seventh tier of English football. [95]
*   Worcester Sorcerers Baseball Club, whose home ground is Norton Parish Hall.
*   Worcester Hockey Club has teams competing in the [West Hockey Leagues](/West_Hockey_Association_(field_hockey)). [96]
*   Worcester St Johns Cycling Club.
*   [Worcester Wolves](/Worcester_Wolves), a professional [basketball](/Basketball) team in the [British Basketball League](/British_Basketball_League), plays at the Worcester Arena.
*   [Worcester Racecourse](/Worcester_Racecourse) is located on the open area known as "Pitchcroft" on the east bank of the [River Severn](/River_Severn).
*   Worcester Rugby Football Club is an amateur rugby union club, founded in 1871. [97]
*   [Worcester Raiders F.C.](/Worcester_Raiders_F.C.), a professional football club.
*   [Worcester Warriors](/Worcester_Warriors), a professional rugby union club.
*   Worcester City Women FC, a National League Women's team, who play at Sixways Stadium.

### Culture

#### Festivals and shows

Every three years, Worcester hosts the [Three Choirs Festival](/Three_Choirs_Festival), an event dating from the 18th century and credited as the oldest music festival in the British Isles. The location rotates between the cathedral cities of [Gloucester](/Gloucester), [Hereford](/Hereford), and Worcester. Known for championing English music, particularly the works of [Elgar](/Edward_Elgar), [Vaughan Williams](/Ralph_Vaughan_Williams), and [Gustav Holst](/Gustav_Holst), Worcester last hosted the festival in July 2017 and, after postponing its 2020 event, held it in 2021. [98] [99] The Worcester Festival, established in 2003 by Chris Jaeger MBE, takes place in August and features a mix of music, theatre, [cinema](/Film), and workshops, alongside a beer festival. [100] For one weekend each year, the city is taken over by the [Worcester Music Festival](/Worcester_Music_Festival), showcasing original music performed mainly by local bands and musicians. All performances are free and held in venues across the city center.

Founded in 2012, the Worcester Film Festival aims to put Worcestershire on the filmmaking map and encourage local participation in film. The inaugural festival took place at [the Hive](/Worcester_Library:_The_Hive) and included screenings, workshops, and talks. [101]

The Victorian-themed Christmas Fayre is a major event in late November/early December, with over 200 stalls lining the streets and attracting more than 100,000 visitors. [102] The [CAMRA](/Campaign_for_Real_Ale) Worcester Beer, Cider and Perry Festival is held over three days each August on Pitchcroft Race Course. [103] It is the largest beer festival in the West Midlands and ranks among the UK's top ten, with attendances of around 14,000. [104] The Worcester Vegan Market, which began in 2021, takes place in late spring and autumn, filling High Street and Cathedral Square with vegan vendors and food trucks. [105] [106]

#### Arts and cinema

The 18th-century actress [Sarah Siddons](/Sarah_Siddons) made her acting debut at the Theatre Royal on Angel Street. Her sister, the novelist Ann Julia Kemble Hatton, also known as Ann of Swansea, was born in the city. [107] Also born in Worcester was Matilda Alice Powles, who achieved fame as [Vesta Tilley](/Vesta_Tilley), a leading [male impersonator](/Cross-dressing) and music hall artiste. [108]

The [Swan Theatre](/Swan_Theatre,_Worcester) [109] stages both professional touring shows and local amateur productions and is the home of the [Worcester Repertory Company](/Worcester_Repertory_Company). Past artistic directors have included [John Doyle](/John_Doyle_(director)) and [David Wood OBE](/David_Wood_(actor)). As of 2019, the director is Sarah-Jane Morgan. [110] Stars who began their careers with the company include [Imelda Staunton](/Imelda_Staunton), [Sean Pertwee](/Sean_Pertwee), [Celia Imrie](/Celia_Imrie), [Rufus Norris](/Rufus_Norris), [Kevin Whately](/Kevin_Whately), and [Bonnie Langford](/Bonnie_Langford). [ [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) ]

[Huntingdon Hall](/Huntingdon_Hall), a historic church, now serves as a venue for a diverse range of musical and comedy performances. [109] Past performers have included [Van Morrison](/Van_Morrison), [Eddie Izzard](/Eddie_Izzard), [Jack Dee](/Jack_Dee), [Omid Djalili](/Omid_Djalili), and [Jason Manford](/Jason_Manford). The Marrs Bar on Pierpoint Street is another venue for gigs and stand-up comedy. [111]

Worcester has two multi-screen cinemas: the Vue Cinema complex on Friar Street and the Odeon on Foregate Street. After being closed for decades, the Scala building on Angel Place, which originally opened as a cinema in 1922, is set to be transformed into a new cultural venue for live performances, film, workshops, and festivals. Work is slated to begin in early 2025, with an expected opening in late 2026. [112] [113]

The northern suburb of [Northwick](/Northwick_(Worcestershire)) is home to the [Art Deco](/Art_Deco) Northwick Cinema. Built in 1938, it contains one of only two remaining cinema interiors in Britain designed by John Alexander. It served as a [bingo](/Housie) hall from 1966 to 1982, then lay empty until it was briefly a music venue in the 1990s. In 2006, it was repurposed as an antiques and lifestyle center. [114]

