### In popular culture

The economic depression that struck the Worcester glove industry in the 1820s and 1830s provides the backdrop for *Mildred Arkell*, a three-volume novel by the Victorian writer [Ellen Wood](/Ellen_Wood_(author)) (then Mrs Henry Wood). [115]

The meticulously researched historical novel [The Virgin in the Ice](/The_Virgin_in_the_Ice), part of [Ellis Peters](/Ellis_Peters)' [The Cadfael Chronicles](/The_Cadfael_Chronicles) series, vividly depicts Worcester during the time of the Anarchy. It opens with the lines:

>"It was early in November of 1139 that the tide of civil war, lately so sluggish and inactive, rose suddenly to wash over the city of Worcester, wash away half of its livestock, property and women and send all those of its inhabitants who could get away in time scurrying for their lives northwards away from the marauders." (The marauders are mentioned as arriving from [Gloucester](/Gloucester), an event that left a long-lasting bitterness between the two cities.)

### Twinning

Worcester is twinned with:
*   [Kleve](/Kleve), Germany (the hometown of [Anne of Cleves](/Anne_of_Cleves), fourth wife of [Henry VIII](/Henry_VIII))
*   [Le Vésinet](/Le_V%C3%A9sinet), France
*   [Worcester](/Worcester,_Massachusetts), Massachusetts, US [116]
*   [Ukmergė](/Ukmerg%C4%97), Lithuania

